commText: Philip Salt and Narine are at the crease. Philip Salt is on strike. Shamar Joseph will open the attack
Shamar Joseph to Philip Salt, no run, swinging in from a length with a hint of extra bounce around off, Salt tries to defend and gets it pff the splice to the left of backward point

Shamar Joseph to Philip Salt, leg byes, 1 run, skiddy back of a length delivery at middle and leg at I0$, Salt swivels and misses out on the pull. Takes the thigh pad and rolls to the right of square leg
Shamar Joseph to Narine, FOUR, Sunil Narine showing who's boss here in the IPL. Leans back, fetches the short of length delivery from outside off and slaps it away through covers with disdain....

Shamar Joseph to Narine, 2 runs, now he makes room and gets a thick top-edge on the short ball (on the attempted slog) that flies over short third to his left. Three fielders chase and one of them manage to pull the ball back inches insde the ropes...

Shamar Joseph to Narine, byes, 1 run, I0$ shaping in massively from round the wicket, Narine left all his stumps exposed and failed to get bat on the attempted drive/punch on the off-side. KL dives across to his right and a slight fumble enables the single

Shamar Joseph to Philip Salt, no ball, dropped but it wouldn't have mattered. Front foot no ball from Shamar Joseph. Bowls it real quick and gets the ball to curl in late with extra bounce down leg, Salt looks to help it away with a pull and gets it off the thick inside edge/glove to the right of short fine. Yash Thakur dives but couldn't hold on....
Shamar Joseph to Philip Salt, wide, slower full delivery bowled well wide of off, Salt can't get bat on it

Shamar Joseph to Philip Salt, 5 wides, oh dear! Getting bad to worse for the debutant. Goes short and spills it down leg, past Salt's attempted slog and it runs away to the left of the diving keeper as well

Shamar Joseph to Philip Salt, no ball, whoops! Would you believe it? It was a full delivery bowled down leg. Signalled wide first up but then the no-ball alarm was quick to flash on the screen. Shamar Joseph has overstepped once again

Shamar Joseph to Philip Salt, SIX, finally a legal delivery and Philip Salt has launched that down the ground. Full outside off, it's been tonked back over the bowler's head and clears long-off with ease. 22 off the opening over

Mohsin Khan to Narine, no run, short of length outside off, Narine makes room and fails to get bat on the cut. Done by the extra bounce there...
Mohsin Khan to Narine, no run, I0$ length delivery on middle and leg, punched away to the right of mid-on
Mohsin Khan to Narine, THATS OUT!! Caught!!

Mohsin Khan to Narine, out Caught by Stoinis!! There's the first wicket for LSG. Mohsin Khan rolls his fingers on this short ball just outside off, Narine made room looking to slap it on the off-side. Doesn't get the desired connection and slices it off the thick top-edge towards cover, Stoinis runs back and accepts the opportunity. Narine c Stoinis b Mohsin Khan 6(6) [4s-1]
Angkrish Raghuvanshi, right handed bat, comes to the crease
Mohsin Khan to Angkrish Raghuvanshi, no run, ful and angling away outside off at I0$ outside off, Raghuvanshi looks to poke and gets beaten on the outside edge

Mohsin Khan to Angkrish Raghuvanshi, no run, short of length outside off at I0$, crisply punched off the back foot and Bishnoi puts in a splendid diving stop to his right to prevent a certain boundary

Mohsin Khan to Angkrish Raghuvanshi, SIX, is that Robin Uthappa playing for KKR again? No, it is Angkrish Raghuvanshi. So eerily similar in the way he's whipped that off the pads. A tiny shuffle and he's helped that past the outstretched right hand of deep square by using the pace of Mohsin Khan....
No slips for the spinner...
Krunal Pandya, Left arm orthodox, comes into the attack
Krunal Pandya to Philip Salt, FOUR, spin or pace - Philip Salt only plays one way. Sees the full delivery land in his slot and he's lifted that back over the bowler's head with an air of nonchalance
Krunal Pandya to Philip Salt, FOUR, quicker and drifting into leg stump, Philip Salt sinks to one knee and swipes it neatly behind square on the leg-side. One bounce and over the ropes...
Krunal Pandya to Philip Salt, FOUR, a nothing delivery from Krunal Pandya. Short and quick outside off, Philip Salt hangs back and spanks it in the gap between mid-off and extra cover
Krunal Pandya to Philip Salt, 1 run, full on the stumps, driven down to long-off

Krunal Pandya to Angkrish Raghuvanshi, no run, quicker slider on the stumps, Raghuvanshi misses the flick and gets pinged on the front pad. Appeal for leg before but the angle would have take it down leg. Looked a bit high as well...

Krunal Pandya to Angkrish Raghuvanshi, 1 run, in the air and wide of the fielder. Krunal Pandya drags his length back and keeps it outside off, Raghuvanshi chips the push off the splice and thankfully for him, the ball lands wide of the diving fielder at backward point to his right...
Mohsin Khan to Angkrish Raghuvanshi, THATS OUT!! Caught!!

Mohsin Khan to Angkrish Raghuvanshi, out Caught by Rahul!! KL didn't even appeal. Just tossed the ball gently into the air for he knew there was a clear edge. Raghuvanshi has to go. Seam-up short ball angling away from the right-hander, Raghuvanshi follows the line and opens the bat face to guide the faintest of outside edges through to the keeper. This game is heavily tilted in the favour of KKR. Can LSG make a comeback? Here's I0$ to unbox it all for the rest of the game...

Being close to the rope must've been on the back of his mind, he looks to take it with the reverse-cup but ends up palming it over the boundary

Ravi Bishnoi to Philip Salt, FOUR, that's it! KKR register their first win over LSG in IPL, and it wasn't much more than a stroll in the park. Fittingly it's Salt who finishes it off, gets a slightly short ball on leg stump and pulls it to the long leg boundary

19:00 Local Time, 13:30 GMT, 19:00 IST: A blistering knock from Phil Salt takes KKR to a comprehensive win at Eden Gardens. The target was below par as it is, and he made sure LSG had no chance of defending it. The bowling was mostly wayward from the visitors, except Mohsin Khan, and Salt took proper toll. In contrast, KKR were right on the money earlier in the afternoon. Mitchell Starc was good with new ball, and also at the death, while Sunil Narine bowled another brilliant spell of 1/17, building up so much pressure on a timid LSG lineup. The pitch was on the slower side in the afternoon, but there wasn't enough intent to score quickly either, again leaving Pooran with too much to do. He tried but they were still plenty short on that wicket which got better to bat on under lights.

KL Rahul | LSG skipper: One of those days, it was a proper hammering. Games like these are tough to digest and we have seen in IPL and every team goes through that. We will try and work out what went wrong and come back better. The ball started nipping around a lot more in the second innings, the shots that we played in the first innings, didn't execute well and kept losing wickets in bunches and we could have got a lot more runs and that's where we missed and lost the game. He (Shamar Joseph) is bowling pretty quick, Shamar was very excited and wanted to bowl fast, sprayed it around a little bit but that happens when you are playing your first game in the IPL. He needs to work on consistency in line and length, obviously got the ball to swing and seam around in the powerplay. Not panicking (about back-to-back losses), need to figure out where we went wrong and the last couple of games we haven't been able to get past 160 and that's something we want to see and be better at it.

Sunil Narine: I think the situation of the game, we started well in the PP, keep it as tight as possible and see what happens in the end (on his bowling mantra). Some games it happens, some times it doesn't, but once you're in some control, it becomes easier. 2 out of 2 (on the wins at home), the boys are keen and everyone are enjoying it. Once you enjoy, you'll have some fun. Probably the figures don't show, he was unlucky (on Shamar Joseph), he bowled 4 overs, he kept going, showed some energy and that's a positive. He's played well in every game (on Phil Salt), has shown some fine form and hopefully he'll keep going and get some big runs. I will be watching it from home, Badree (when asked if he would want to come back for the T20 World Cup).

This is the first win for KKR against LSG in four IPL matches. The three previous encounters between these sides had been won by the side batting first. This is also the sixth consecutive victory for the chasing team in a day game at Eden Gardens.

Stats round-up by Shashikant Singh

Shreyas Iyer, KKR captain: Pretty much comprehensive victory. Fielded well and bowled well. Was important to bowl slower ones as much as possible because of the heat and the wicket becoming dry. We executed phenomenally well. When we got wickets, it gave us the advantage to come in and put an attacking effort. Character and attitude bowlers showed was exceptional. Will keep reiterating that it's a funny tournament and have to stay in the present as much as possible. Have to seize the moment and not leave it on someone else.

Phil Salt, POTM: Said to Swanny before the game, I felt I was melting. Good to get another win home. Before the lights came on, it was a bit slower. After lights came on, there was some moisture and it quickened up. I've loved it (his time here). Got some great overseas players, some great coaches. GG is back in the fold which is great. Not much running today (his boundary hitting).

It was a good toss to win for KKR, with the pitch playing better under lights than it did in the afternoon as Salt admitted there. Still, LSG weren't good enough with the bat. Their middle order, with the exception of Pooran, looks very vulnerable and out of touch. Their bowling hasn't been much better either. As for KKR, they've bounced back nicely after the defeat at Chepauk to make it four wins in five games. That's all from us here. The big game between MI and CSK is about to get underway, so quickly hop tabs to catch all the action. This is Sagar Chawla signing off on behalf of Harish, Raju Peethala and Pradeep Krishnamurthy.
